        <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
          <tr>
          <td align="left" valign="center">
          <font size="+1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#F52E00>
          <b>Features</b>
          </font>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr><td colspan=2 height=1><img src=../../../img/blank.gif width=1 height=1></td></tr>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
        </table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The diagram below shows the function of the three connectors of the <b>A100</b>.
The device is inser&shy;ted between the host (laptop) and the (insecure)
network. It has no physical controls or indica&shy;tors. Instead it is
controlled via a web-interface (https) that is accessible via the red interface.
<br />
          <br />
          <table 
           border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"><tr><td align="center" valign=top>
            <div style="position: relative;">
            <div style="position: relative;">
            <img src="svg/a100_ext.svg"
             style="
             max-width: 618px;
            "
             align="center"
             vspace="4"
             border=0
            
             />
            </div>
            </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
          </td></tr></table>
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <a name=int></a>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
          <tr>
          <td align="left" valign="center">
          <font size="+1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#F52E00>
          <b>Interior</b>
          </font>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr><td colspan=2 height=1><img src=../../../img/blank.gif width=1 height=1></td></tr>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
        </table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The interior of the device can be accessed by
<a href="img/304235/004/full.jpg"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: removing four recessed screws">removing four recessed screws</span></a>
from the <a href="img/304235/003/full.jpg"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: aluminium bottom panel">aluminium bottom panel</span></a>, after which the
<a href="img/304235/005/full.jpg"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: bottom can be removed">bottom can be removed</span></a> from the carbon fibre case
shell. With a bit of wiggeling, the
<a href="img/304235/018/full.jpg"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: interior can now be removed">interior can now be removed</span></a>
from the case shell. The device consists of two printed circuit
boards (<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Printed Circuit Board">PCB</span>s): a <a href="img/304235/009/full.jpg"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: carrier board">carrier board</span></a>
with the interfaces, and a <a href="img/304235/011/full.jpg"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: separate processor board">separate processor board</span></a>.
The image below shows the carrier board, which is marked <div style="display:inline-block; font-family:monospace; font-size:14px;">'MMCnetDUO'</div>.
At the <a href="img/304235/009/full.jpg"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: bottom side">bottom side</span></a> (vi&shy;si&shy;ble here) are two
LAN91C111 ethernet controllers plus a receptacle for an <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Multi-Media Card">MMC</span> storage card.
<br />
          <br />
          <table 
           border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"><tr><td align="center" valign=top>
<a href="img/304235/009/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Click to see more">
<a href="img/304235/009/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Click to see more">
            <img src="img/a100_int1.png"
             style="
            "
             align="center"
             width="610px"
             vspace="4"
             alt="Click to see more"
             border=0
             />
            </div>
            </a>
            </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
          </td></tr></table>
<br />
The <a href="img/304235/014/full.jpg"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: upper side of the carrier board">upper side of the carrier board</span></a> &ndash; shown below &ndash;
holds two RJ45 sockets with built-in mag&shy;netics, for connection of the
laptop and the (insecure) network respectively. It also hold the power socket.
Fitted to the carrier board is a Gumstix Verdex Pro daughter board,
built around a Marvell PXA270 application processor. The latter contains
an Intel Xscale <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Advanced RISC Machines">ARM</span> processor, which runs at 200 MHz. The Gumstix board has
64MB <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Random Access Memory">RAM</span>, 16MB Flash <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Read-Only Memory">ROM</span> and a MicroSD card reader <a href="#ref_2">[2]</a>.
<br />
          <br />
          <table 
           border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"><tr><td align="center" valign=top>
<a href="img/304235/011/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Click to see more">
<a href="img/304235/011/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Click to see more">
            <img src="img/a100_int2.png"
             style="
            "
             align="center"
             width="607px"
             vspace="4"
             alt="Click to see more"
             border=0
             />
            </div>
            </a>
            </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
          </td></tr></table>
<br />
At the time of the development (2007), the Verdex Pro board was a readily
available processor board, made by Gumstix, Inc. (<span class="short" aria-label="United States of America (USA)" data-balloon-pos="up"><a href="../../usa" class="short" >US</a></span>) <a href="#ref_2">[2]</a>.
The MMCnetDUO carrier board was developed by
<a href="../index.htm"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: Tutus Data AB">Tutus Data AB</span></a> in Sweden,
along with the firmware for the Verdex
board and the device's enclosure.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
